Hey. Man. You know where
I could find Frank Barnes?

14
00:03:09,809 --> 00:03:10,998
- Sir?
- Frank Barnes.

15
00:03:15,083 --> 00:03:16,033
Good luck.

16
00:03:16,292 --> 00:03:17,231
Thanks.

17
00:03:24,846 --> 00:03:27,119
Excuse me.
I'm looking for Frank Barnes.

18
00:03:28,049 --> 00:03:28,960
You found him.

19
00:03:29,046 --> 00:03:30,082
I'm Will Colson.

20
00:03:30,169 --> 00:03:32,758
We're working together
today on train 1206.

21
00:03:33,890 --> 00:03:35,357
1206.
That's the one.

22
00:03:35,491 --> 00:03:37,361
That's the profile?
Yeah. Want to take a look?

23
00:03:39,327 --> 00:03:40,756
How you doing?

24
00:03:47,086 --> 00:03:48,083
Is there a problem?

25
00:03:48,927 --> 00:03:50,039
No problem.

26
00:03:50,126 --> 00:03:52,677
I just don't like working
in a damn day-care center.

27
00:03:53,645 --> 00:03:56,359
Yeah. Well. I don't like working
at a retirement home. So...

28
00:03:56,446 --> 00:03:58,354
All right.
I'll tell you what.

29
00:03:58,450 --> 00:04:00,521
I'm going to finish my coffee.
I'll meet you on the wagon.

30
00:04:00,886 --> 00:04:02,075
Sounds good.

31
00:04:02,363 --> 00:04:04,396
1206.
Yeah. That's the one.

32
00:04:07,004 --> 00:04:08,673
You know that punk's
union. Right?

33
00:04:09,162 --> 00:04:11,071
Heard they just made him
a shop steward at the UTU.

34
00:04:11,167 --> 00:04:12,595
First year?

35
00:04:12,682 --> 00:04:15,118
You know how he got
hired? His name's Colson.

36
00:04:15,808 --> 00:04:17,112
His two uncles are running
things over at Thornwood

37
00:04:17,208 --> 00:04:19,683
and his brother's
lead welder at Deacon.

38
00:04:20,210 --> 00:04:21,486
The whole family's
from Stanton.

39
00:04:22,042 --> 00:04:23,202
That figures.

40
00:04:23,567 --> 00:04:25,111
Here. They're shit-canning
guys every day.

41
00:04:25,207 --> 00:04:27,326
But you got the right last
name and a rookie's pay grade.

42
00:04:29,004 --> 00:04:30,433
You got a job.

43
00:04:39,045 --> 00:04:40,685
What the hell are these guys?

44
00:04:42,565 --> 00:04:44,042
Dewey. Gilleece.

45
00:04:44,329 --> 00:04:45,960
Sorry to break up
charm school,

46
00:04:46,765 --> 00:04:49,604
but what the hell is that
beast still doing on D-16?

47
00:04:49,968 --> 00:04:51,560
I told you I need
that track clear.

48
00:04:52,366 --> 00:04:54,485
Relax. Buddy. We were
just about to move it.

49
00:04:54,562 --> 00:04:55,838
Like hell you are.

50
00:04:55,924 --> 00:04:59,319
I've got 150 school students coming
in on some field trip on D-16.

51
00:04:59,405 --> 00:05:00,805
I need that track cleared.

52
00:05:00,882 --> 00:05:02,522
D-10's clear.
You can set it there.

53
00:05:06,444 --> 00:05:09,676
All right. All right.
Settle down. Settle down.

54
00:05:09,964 --> 00:05:12,956
Welcome to the
Railroad Safety Campaign.

55
00:05:13,042 --> 00:05:14,471
We're a not-for-profit program

56
00:05:14,567 --> 00:05:18,077
designed to educate young people
like yourselves about railway safety.

57
00:05:18,163 --> 00:05:19,880
Hey. Settle down.

58
00:05:20,321 --> 00:05:21,319
Show of hands.

59
00:05:21,645 --> 00:05:22,949
Who's ridden a train before?

60
00:05:23,045 --> 00:05:24,272
Me!
Me!

61
00:05:24,368 --> 00:05:26,958
All right! All aboard!

62
00:05:31,005 --> 00:05:32,635
So what's our day?

63
00:05:33,805 --> 00:05:35,637
They got us going
on light power.

64
00:05:35,723 --> 00:05:37,958
We're supposed to pick up
25 cars just past Stanton

65
00:05:38,044 --> 00:05:39,713
then it's pretty much a
straight shot through Wilkins.

66
00:05:40,039 --> 00:05:41,391
Any slow orders?

67
00:05:41,487 --> 00:05:43,242
No.
You sure?

68
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:46,589
They'd be highlighted in red.

69
00:05:47,164 --> 00:05:49,159
No. No slow orders.

70
00:05:50,281 --> 00:05:51,230
All right.

71
00:05:57,205 --> 00:05:59,353
Dewey, what
the hell is taking you so long?

72
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:01,712
It's a 39-car consist.
Bunny.

73
00:06:01,799 --> 00:06:04,043
The thing's half a mile long.
For Christ's sake.

74
00:06:08,004 --> 00:06:09,432
Gilleece. Channel up.

75
00:06:11,044 --> 00:06:12,434
Go for Gilleece.

76
00:06:12,521 --> 00:06:13,921
You believe this shit?

77
00:06:16,366 --> 00:06:18,840
Hey. Hold up. You forgot to
tie the air in from the point.

78
00:06:19,406 --> 00:06:20,519
Yeah. So?

79
00:06:20,643 --> 00:06:23,003
So. You don't
have any air brakes.

80
00:06:23,079 --> 00:06:24,508
You can tie the hoses
once we got her parked

81
00:06:24,604 --> 00:06:26,148
and Bunny's quit
his bitching.

82
00:06:26,244 --> 00:06:27,280
Okay.

83
00:06:38,481 --> 00:06:40,198
I only got one rule.

84
00:06:40,284 --> 00:06:41,713
One rule only.

85
00:06:41,799 --> 00:06:43,228
You going to do something.
You do it right.

86
00:06:43,324 --> 00:06:44,993
You don't know how to
do it. Ask me. All right?

87
00:06:45,079 --> 00:06:47,553
Likewise. If you need anything
from me. You better speak up

88
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:49,913
'cause you're
the conductor.

89
00:06:49,999 --> 00:06:51,552
Once we get our freight.
It's your train.

90
00:06:51,639 --> 00:06:53,394
I'm just the guy
driving it.

91
00:06:54,123 --> 00:06:55,398
How long you been
out of training?

92
00:06:55,523 --> 00:06:56,750
About four months.

93
00:06:56,837 --> 00:06:58,630
Four months? Wow.
Yeah.

94
00:06:59,359 --> 00:07:01,392
Full-on yellow vest rookie.

95
00:07:01,478 --> 00:07:02,955
How long you
been railroading?

96
00:07:03,042 --> 00:07:06,791
Twenty-eight years.
November 13. 1981. 28 years.

97
00:07:06,878 --> 00:07:08,470
What did you do
before that?

98
00:07:08,604 --> 00:07:11,347
Oh. I don't know.
A bunch of different jobs.

99
00:07:11,442 --> 00:07:13,437
Yeah? No railroading?
No.

100
00:07:14,003 --> 00:07:16,429
Just looking to do
something different.

101
00:07:17,082 --> 00:07:19,230
Something different?

102
00:07:19,326 --> 00:07:20,678
What do you mean.
Something better?

103
00:07:21,081 --> 00:07:22,874
No. Just...

104
00:07:23,200 --> 00:07:25,435
Different.
Just different.

105
00:07:30,920 --> 00:07:33,068
Hey. Dewey. Want to pick
it up a little bit. Jag off?

106
00:07:33,164 --> 00:07:35,552
I want to have
lunch at some point.

107
00:07:59,921 --> 00:08:01,311
- Yeah.
- Hey.

108
00:08:01,484 --> 00:08:04,198
Your lawyer just called.
You got a break.

109
00:08:04,639 --> 00:08:06,356
The hearing's been
moved up to this morning.

110
00:08:06,442 --> 00:08:08,514
Looks like
you'll be going home.

111
00:08:13,079 --> 00:08:14,555
Well. That's great.
But...

112
00:08:16,004 --> 00:08:17,068
Did you tell him
I was working?

113
00:08:17,164 --> 00:08:18,152
I can't come in.

114
00:08:18,238 --> 00:08:20,597
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah.
He said no problem. Man.

115
00:08:20,684 --> 00:08:22,554
It's looking good.
All right.

116
00:08:25,364 --> 00:08:27,032
Call him in an hour or two.
See where it's at.

117
00:08:27,119 --> 00:08:28,308
I will.
And then give me a call.

118
00:08:30,082 --> 00:08:31,434
We ready to
pull out or what?

119
00:08:32,316 --> 00:08:33,630
Coming.

120
00:08:34,397 --> 00:08:35,711
All right.

121
00:08:36,162 --> 00:08:37,553
Train is leaving.

122
00:08:44,199 --> 00:08:45,752
What's our
fuel gauge reading?

123
00:08:46,596 --> 00:08:48,188
Fuel gauge.
2.900.

124
00:08:48,274 --> 00:08:49,387
2.900!

125
00:08:50,442 --> 00:08:52,705
Angle-cock's closed.
Hand brake's knocked off.

126
00:08:52,801 --> 00:08:53,865
Good. Good. Good.

127
00:08:53,961 --> 00:08:55,630
Got all the updated division
notices and bulletin orders.

128
00:08:55,716 --> 00:08:56,752
The POS releases are in.

129
00:08:56,838 --> 00:08:58,593
Filled out our time slips.
We're good to go.

130
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:00,511
Good. All right.

131
00:09:16,316 --> 00:09:18,915
You're at 29 cars. You
got 10 to go. You're good.

132
00:09:20,440 --> 00:09:22,703
Dewey, you got 29.
Ten more makes...

133
00:09:24,314 --> 00:09:26,319
You taking PB-9
over to D-10?

134
00:09:29,915 --> 00:09:31,229
Dewey.

135
00:09:31,401 --> 00:09:32,706
Dewey.

136
00:09:32,955 --> 00:09:34,269
Hold your horses.

137
00:09:36,360 --> 00:09:37,309
What's wrong?

138
00:09:37,760 --> 00:09:41,433
Damn trailing point switch.
The track's aligned for D-16.

139
00:09:41,797 --> 00:09:43,591
What's your
stopping distance?

140
00:09:43,715 --> 00:09:45,863
At least 20 cars
to a stop. Damn it!

141
00:09:45,959 --> 00:09:47,868
Okay. So we back it up
and lose a little time.

142
00:09:50,438 --> 00:09:51,838
I'm hopping out.

143
00:09:52,039 --> 00:09:53,392
Do not get out
of that cab. Man!

144
00:09:53,516 --> 00:09:55,789
Don't worry.
I'll set the independent.

145
00:09:55,876 --> 00:09:58,474
Dewey! Dewey!

146
00:10:05,801 --> 00:10:07,825
Come on,
get back on.

147
00:10:07,921 --> 00:10:09,791
Dewey!
You better get back on!

148
00:10:09,916 --> 00:10:11,795
I'm on it. I'm on it.

149
00:10:32,759 --> 00:10:34,227
Shit!

150
00:10:39,194 --> 00:10:40,547
You better get
back on. Dickhead.

151
00:10:46,560 --> 00:10:47,499
Hey!

152
00:10:55,239 --> 00:10:56,706
Shit!

153
00:10:56,831 --> 00:10:58,355
Nice job. Dewey!

154
00:11:14,793 --> 00:11:16,347
God damn it!

155
00:11:17,632 --> 00:11:18,984
So now what the hell
do we do?

156
00:11:38,433 --> 00:11:39,747
Shoot.

157
00:11:51,073 --> 00:11:53,624
Ooh. You're in trouble.

158
00:11:54,036 --> 00:11:56,990
Just don't talk about it. Just put
your sister on the phone. Sweetheart.

159
00:11:59,032 --> 00:12:00,193
Dad.

160
00:12:01,238 --> 00:12:02,590
She doesn't want
to talk to you.

161
00:12:02,878 --> 00:12:06,426
Listen. Just tell her I was...
I didn't forget. I was just...

162
00:12:06,753 --> 00:12:08,469
I was running late.

163
00:12:08,958 --> 00:12:10,550
She's got a date tonight.

164
00:12:11,711 --> 00:12:12,871
With who?

165
00:12:14,031 --> 00:12:15,432
Just put your
sister on the phone.

166
00:12:15,796 --> 00:12:17,311
Wait. Here she is.

167
00:12:23,871 --> 00:12:24,945
Nic?

168
00:12:26,115 --> 00:12:27,180
Nicky?

169
00:12:28,196 --> 00:12:29,146
Hello?

170
00:12:29,232 --> 00:12:30,824
Listen. Just...

171
00:12:30,910 --> 00:12:32,627
Baby, look, I didn't forget. I was...

172
00:12:51,510 --> 00:12:54,138
Frank. The stop blocks
are up. Is there a problem?

173
00:12:54,272 --> 00:12:56,660
No. There's no problem.
Except you got it backwards.

174
00:12:57,513 --> 00:13:00,745
Turntable house goes on my
end. You're on the ballast.

175
00:13:00,832 --> 00:13:02,184
On my end.

176
00:13:02,270 --> 00:13:05,310
Other than that, no problem.
No problem at all.

177
00:13:15,313 --> 00:13:17,307
Like I told you.

178
00:13:17,394 --> 00:13:19,388
If you don't know something.
Just ask. That's all.

179
00:13:20,348 --> 00:13:21,700
I got it.

180
00:13:22,275 --> 00:13:23,579
I hope so.

181
00:13:26,351 --> 00:13:27,300
Whatever.

182
00:13:28,269 --> 00:13:29,266
Excuse me?

183
00:13:30,235 --> 00:13:33,189
This shit. This "Let's make the
new guy prove himself" bullshit.

184
00:13:33,994 --> 00:13:37,217
I got to tell you. I've heard it
before and it gets old real fast.

185
00:13:37,313 --> 00:13:39,547
Well. That's how it is
at the retirement home.

186
00:13:44,112 --> 00:13:46,020
Company wants to get
rid of us old heads.

187
00:13:46,433 --> 00:13:49,991
They give all the jobs to you
new guys. You yellow vests.

188
00:13:50,432 --> 00:13:52,312
I'm not trying to take
anything from anybody.

189
00:13:52,388 --> 00:13:54,297
As reassuring as that is.

190
00:13:55,227 --> 00:13:57,624
A lot of guys
don't see it that way.

191
00:14:20,027 --> 00:14:22,271
I'm here.
I'm walking in right now.

192
00:14:22,386 --> 00:14:24,822
I got a car full of donuts
for those kids.

193
00:14:26,031 --> 00:14:27,747
A coaster? What train?

194
00:14:28,706 --> 00:14:29,780
How the hell
did this happen?

195
00:14:29,915 --> 00:14:30,950
It just got away from me.

196
00:14:31,065 --> 00:14:32,907
It got away from you?

197
00:14:33,031 --> 00:14:34,786
It's a train. Dewey.
Not a chipmunk.

198
00:14:34,873 --> 00:14:37,261
I had to leave the cab
to throw a switch.

199
00:14:37,347 --> 00:14:38,987
- You left the cab?
- Yeah.

200
00:14:39,073 --> 00:14:40,349
And it gets worse.

201
00:14:41,547 --> 00:14:44,338
The air brakes weren't tied
on. They aren't tied on. Still.

202
00:14:45,105 --> 00:14:48,577
We've got an unmanned train
rolling into opposing traffic

203
00:14:48,673 --> 00:14:50,303
with no air brakes. Is
that what you're telling me?

204
00:14:50,390 --> 00:14:52,269
I set the independent brakes.
That will for sure stop it.

205
00:14:52,346 --> 00:14:53,535
How fast is it going?

206
00:14:53,669 --> 00:14:54,897
No more than 10 miles per.

207
00:14:55,031 --> 00:14:56,499
Okay. Jump on the
hi-rail and go after it.

208
00:14:57,793 --> 00:14:58,829
Now!

209
00:14:58,906 --> 00:14:59,855
Okay. Ballbuster.

210
00:15:08,831 --> 00:15:09,867
Call the field trip!

211
00:15:09,954 --> 00:15:11,306
I don't care where
they are on the main line.

212
00:15:11,392 --> 00:15:12,428
They need to get
into the nearest siding.

213
00:15:13,425 --> 00:15:16,178
RS Campaign. RS Campaign. This
is Fuller Yard. Do you copy?

214
00:15:19,870 --> 00:15:22,373
RSC answering dispatch.
How can I help you? Over.

215
00:15:22,747 --> 00:15:24,099
RS Campaign.
This is Fuller Yard.

216
00:15:24,185 --> 00:15:26,017
We've got unauthorized
activity on your track.

217
00:15:26,113 --> 00:15:28,376
We're going to need you to divert
to a siding at Portville.

218
00:15:30,592 --> 00:15:31,982
Dispatch. Please repeat.

219
00:15:32,951 --> 00:15:34,581
Please repeat. Over.

220
00:15:34,706 --> 00:15:37,065
What time is train time?

221
00:15:37,151 --> 00:15:38,580
Anytime!

222
00:15:39,232 --> 00:15:41,582
Divert to a siding
in Portville. Do you copy?

223
00:15:41,668 --> 00:15:43,941
I copy. I'll divert into the
siding at Portville. Over.

224
00:15:49,945 --> 00:15:52,332
Get me 777's
cargo information.

225
00:15:52,428 --> 00:15:53,944
I have to call corporate
and report this.

226
00:15:55,027 --> 00:15:57,818
Now. Dewey said
he applied the independent.

227
00:15:57,904 --> 00:16:00,705
So friction should stop the
damn thing after a few miles.

228
00:16:00,791 --> 00:16:03,054
Still. We need to alert every
northbound train on the mainline.

229
00:16:03,150 --> 00:16:05,059
First 20 miles of
track take priority.

230
00:16:09,029 --> 00:16:10,333
I don't care if
you're talking about

231
00:16:10,429 --> 00:16:12,213
a spot weld on
a Class 3 rip track

232
00:16:12,309 --> 00:16:15,704
or ground operations in Afghanistan.
It's all about precision.

233
00:16:15,790 --> 00:16:16,778
- Right.
- Thank you.

234
00:16:17,986 --> 00:16:19,540
- Excuse me.
- Sure.

235
00:16:20,067 --> 00:16:21,055
Hello.

236
00:16:21,467 --> 00:16:22,532
Ned. Where are you?

237
00:16:22,628 --> 00:16:25,582
Oh. Connie.
I'm just driving in now.

238
00:16:25,668 --> 00:16:26,857
I got to go.

239
00:16:26,943 --> 00:16:28,497
How far are you
from milepost 5?

240
00:16:28,583 --> 00:16:30,943
Roughly six minutes.
Traffic contingent.

241
00:16:31,067 --> 00:16:32,784
Great. I need you to
haul ass over there

242
00:16:32,870 --> 00:16:34,577
and throw the siding switch.
We got a coaster.

243
00:16:34,711 --> 00:16:36,064
A coaster? Really?

244
00:16:36,150 --> 00:16:38,653
Yeah. It should roll past
MP 5 in about 15 minutes.

245
00:16:38,787 --> 00:16:40,264
That should give you enough
time to throw the switch.

246
00:16:40,350 --> 00:16:42,853
Get it off the mainline
and onto that siding.

247
00:16:42,949 --> 00:16:44,618
You want me to climb
onboard and stop it?

248
00:16:44,704 --> 00:16:47,984
What? No. Two hostlers are on the
way. Just throw the switch. Ned.

249
00:16:48,071 --> 00:16:49,538
Roger that.

250
00:16:49,989 --> 00:16:51,983
You can always
count on him to be late.

251
00:16:52,626 --> 00:16:53,940
I'll see you later.

252
00:16:54,227 --> 00:16:55,177
See you!

253
00:16:55,388 --> 00:16:57,536
Yeah, I can get
you where you need to go

254
00:16:57,622 --> 00:16:58,735
'Cause I'm a country boy

255
00:17:08,622 --> 00:17:10,579
What do we do when we
get to a railroad crossing?

256
00:17:10,665 --> 00:17:13,101
Stop. Look and listen!

257
00:17:13,187 --> 00:17:14,415
I can't hear you!

258
00:17:14,511 --> 00:17:16,774
Stop. Look and listen!

259
00:17:37,901 --> 00:17:39,694
You from Stanton?

260
00:17:40,625 --> 00:17:42,102
Born and raised.
Yeah?

261
00:17:43,224 --> 00:17:45,420
My whole family's
from Stanton.

262
00:17:47,347 --> 00:17:48,537
Married?

263
00:17:49,380 --> 00:17:50,416
Yeah.

264
00:17:52,267 --> 00:17:53,974
Well. Sort of.
It's a long story.

265
00:17:54,060 --> 00:17:55,298
We got a long day.

266
00:18:01,627 --> 00:18:03,296
How about you?
You married?

267
00:18:03,382 --> 00:18:05,454
Short story. Once.

268
00:18:06,144 --> 00:18:08,858
Got two beautiful daughters.
Though. 18. 19.

269
00:18:09,980 --> 00:18:12,416
They are both waitressing. Trying
to work their way through college.

270
00:18:12,502 --> 00:18:13,903
- Oh. Yeah?
- Yeah.

271
00:18:13,989 --> 00:18:15,773
- Where at?
- Hooters.

272
00:18:18,304 --> 00:18:21,335
- Hooters. You know?
- All right.

273
00:18:21,460 --> 00:18:23,819
That's right. Hooters.
Wipe that grin off your face.

274
00:18:24,787 --> 00:18:26,092
- I'm a fan.
- Yeah.

275
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:27,137
You're blushing.

276
00:18:31,222 --> 00:18:32,939
I'm used to it.

277
00:18:34,186 --> 00:18:35,538
I'm used to it.

278
00:18:42,424 --> 00:18:44,495
Connie. Corporate on line 2.

279
00:18:46,461 --> 00:18:48,053
This is Connie Hooper
at Fuller Yard.

280
00:18:49,300 --> 00:18:50,652
I'll hold.

281
00:18:53,347 --> 00:18:54,737
Did I hear right?
You've got a coaster?

282
00:18:56,502 --> 00:18:58,094
Yeah. This sort of thing
happens. We're on it.

283
00:18:58,180 --> 00:18:59,974
Won't it trip a relay?

284
00:19:00,626 --> 00:19:03,532
Listen. I need to speak
to Mr. Galvin directly.

285
00:19:05,421 --> 00:19:07,809
I see. Can you have him call me. Then?

286
00:19:08,308 --> 00:19:10,302
No. I'm about to review
the cargo shipment myself.

287
00:19:13,342 --> 00:19:14,340
Who the hell are you?

288
00:19:14,426 --> 00:19:16,056
I'm here for the
Railroad Safety Campaign.

289
00:19:16,143 --> 00:19:19,614
Scott Werner. FRA Region 2.
Federal Safety Inspector.

290
00:19:19,701 --> 00:19:21,178
I'm supposed to give a
presentation to the children.

291
00:19:21,302 --> 00:19:23,815
Go over some basic stuff.
That's great. Hey. Bunny? Bunny!

292
00:19:23,901 --> 00:19:24,975
Can you help me out here?

293
00:19:25,062 --> 00:19:26,491
Okay. See this
guy right there?

294
00:19:26,586 --> 00:19:27,574
He's going to tell
you where to sit.

295
00:19:27,661 --> 00:19:28,610
Track geometry.
Alignment...

296
00:19:28,706 --> 00:19:29,694
Thank you so much.
I brought some gages...

297
00:19:29,780 --> 00:19:31,775
The kids are going to
love that. It's great.

298
00:19:50,102 --> 00:19:52,816
God damn it. Where
the hell is this thing?

299
00:20:00,382 --> 00:20:03,729
Bunny? I need to know exactly
what's in cars 7 to 10.

300
00:20:03,825 --> 00:20:05,177
Get a hold of
the shipper. Please.

301
00:20:12,619 --> 00:20:14,413
Are you kidding me?

302
00:20:21,260 --> 00:20:22,296
Where's the train?

303
00:20:22,382 --> 00:20:23,897
Where does it look like
the goddamn train is?

304
00:20:24,022 --> 00:20:25,422
It's not here! What
are you doing out here?

305
00:20:25,499 --> 00:20:27,532
Do I look like I got a train
hidden in my back pocket?

306
00:20:27,618 --> 00:20:28,731
Bunny. Get me Connie.
It's Ned.

307
00:20:28,865 --> 00:20:30,016
Get behind us. Jackass.

308
00:20:30,102 --> 00:20:31,646
Did you get here too late?
Don't give me that shit.

309
00:20:31,742 --> 00:20:33,861
You two numbnuts
are always screwing up.

310
00:20:33,938 --> 00:20:36,729
You switched the track that was supposed
to get the train on the right track.

311
00:20:36,825 --> 00:20:38,014
Connie. Yeah. It's Ned.

312
00:20:38,139 --> 00:20:39,328
Did you throw
that switch yet?

313
00:20:39,424 --> 00:20:41,812
Yeah. Six minutes ago. But
your train. It's not here.

314
00:20:41,898 --> 00:20:43,931
I thought it might be going a
little slower than you guessed,

315
00:20:44,017 --> 00:20:45,533
but these two numbnuts
that you sent.

316
00:20:45,619 --> 00:20:46,808
They just showed up and
they haven't seen it. Either.

317
00:20:46,904 --> 00:20:48,496
Are you saying our
train has already passed?

318
00:20:48,582 --> 00:20:50,098
Yes. Ma'am.
That would be my guess.

319
00:20:50,817 --> 00:20:52,610
It's not a coaster.
That train is under power.

320
00:20:52,697 --> 00:20:53,809
That would be my guess. Too.

321
00:20:55,017 --> 00:20:56,446
- Put Dewey on the phone.
- Sure.

322
00:20:56,542 --> 00:20:57,894
She wants to talk
to you. Asshole.

323
00:20:58,019 --> 00:20:59,333
Yeah.

324
00:20:59,419 --> 00:21:01,615
I need you to rally every
cell in that brain of yours.

325
00:21:01,702 --> 00:21:02,853
When you applied
the independent.

326
00:21:02,939 --> 00:21:05,058
Was the throttle in
the forward position?

327
00:21:05,145 --> 00:21:06,813
Yeah. I had to
get it moving!

328
00:21:06,900 --> 00:21:09,211
In what position
was the throttle set?

329
00:21:10,736 --> 00:21:12,165
Damn it. Dewey.
What position?

330
00:21:14,102 --> 00:21:17,056
Connie. The throttle
was in notch 8. Full power.

331
00:21:17,142 --> 00:21:19,213
Okay? It was 39 cars!

332
00:21:24,421 --> 00:21:25,370
Okay.

333
00:21:25,457 --> 00:21:27,653
Take the southbound track.
Catch up.

334
00:21:27,739 --> 00:21:30,252
See if it's still going slow
enough for one of you to climb on.

335
00:21:30,338 --> 00:21:34,337
You have got until milepost 13
before the track splits.

336
00:21:34,423 --> 00:21:35,651
Let me talk to Ned again.

337
00:21:39,381 --> 00:21:41,213
Nice job. Asshole!

338
00:21:43,659 --> 00:21:46,651
Ned. I want you to get back in your
car and follow the mainline. Okay?

339
00:21:46,737 --> 00:21:47,974
I want a set of
eyes on that train.

340
00:21:48,061 --> 00:21:49,768
You got them. Roger that.

341
00:22:00,816 --> 00:22:02,129
I can't hear you!

342
00:22:02,254 --> 00:22:04,930
Railroad Safety Campaign!

343
00:23:00,975 --> 00:23:02,375
You're good.

344
00:23:04,178 --> 00:23:05,722
Keep it coming. 50.

345
00:23:08,177 --> 00:23:09,366
20 feet.

346
00:23:09,855 --> 00:23:10,968
Slow down.

347
00:23:12,982 --> 00:23:14,890
All right. You're good.

348
00:23:29,620 --> 00:23:31,011
Yeah.
What's going on?

349
00:23:31,539 --> 00:23:32,843
You got a minute?

350
00:23:37,341 --> 00:23:38,645
I thought he said
it was looking good.

351
00:23:39,776 --> 00:23:40,841
That's what he thought.

352
00:23:41,292 --> 00:23:43,325
Turns out the judge they
assigned was a real hard-ass.

353
00:23:44,495 --> 00:23:45,847
You got to be kidding me.

354
00:23:45,933 --> 00:23:48,446
Look. The restraining order is
being continued for another 30 days.

355
00:23:48,532 --> 00:23:50,652
Thirty days? What am I
supposed to do for 30 days?

356
00:23:50,738 --> 00:23:52,014
Stay away from my kid?

357
00:23:52,100 --> 00:23:54,047
And then there's another
hearing after that. I guess.

358
00:23:56,339 --> 00:23:58,410
What's taking
you so long. Will?

359
00:23:58,573 --> 00:23:59,925
You call that lawyer.
You can tell him

360
00:24:00,012 --> 00:24:01,326
he can stick it
up his ass. I got to go.

361
00:24:01,412 --> 00:24:02,726
Will, pick up the radio.

362
00:24:03,493 --> 00:24:06,284
Will. Pick up the radio.
Over.

363
00:24:07,540 --> 00:24:08,576
Are you there?

364
00:24:08,652 --> 00:24:09,602
Yeah.

365
00:24:09,938 --> 00:24:12,489
Yeah. Get off the phone.
Knock off the hand brakes.

366
00:24:12,575 --> 00:24:14,694
Get up here. It's time
to go. We got work to do.

367
00:24:14,771 --> 00:24:15,807
Copy.

368
00:24:27,737 --> 00:24:28,773
No. It's definitely
under power.

369
00:24:28,859 --> 00:24:30,250
We're not sure of
the exact speed yet.

370
00:24:30,576 --> 00:24:33,088
I thought all these trains had
some sort of dead-man brake.

371
00:24:33,175 --> 00:24:35,246
There's a wand the engineer
has to hit periodically

372
00:24:35,332 --> 00:24:36,886
or the air brakes are
automatically applied.

373
00:24:36,972 --> 00:24:39,408
Unfortunately. This train's
air brakes were disconnected.

374
00:24:39,696 --> 00:24:43,014
Sir, I would gladly explain the
particulars of locomotive operation to you

375
00:24:43,091 --> 00:24:45,929
if we had time. But right now
I really need your assistance

376
00:24:46,016 --> 00:24:47,847
posting officers at
all the mainline crossings.

377
00:24:47,934 --> 00:24:48,883
One question.

378
00:24:49,775 --> 00:24:51,367
How do you all
plan to stop it?

379
00:24:52,777 --> 00:24:54,004
We're working on it.

380
00:24:56,450 --> 00:24:57,764
Go. Go. Go!
The splits is coming up!

381
00:25:06,376 --> 00:25:07,680
Are you sure
you can do this?

382
00:25:07,776 --> 00:25:09,320
Just get
alongside of the cab.

383
00:25:15,295 --> 00:25:16,723
Get up alongside of it!

384
00:25:16,810 --> 00:25:17,846
I'm trying!

385
00:25:21,778 --> 00:25:23,082
Go. Go. Go!

386
00:25:27,378 --> 00:25:28,682
Remember. We don't have
a lot of track!

387
00:25:35,376 --> 00:25:37,208
You got it. Go. Go!

388
00:25:39,893 --> 00:25:41,246
Dewey!

389
00:25:41,409 --> 00:25:43,202
It's too fast! Back it up!

390
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:45,638
Come on. Dewey! Go back!

391
00:25:54,969 --> 00:25:56,609
Jump. Gilleece! Do it!

392
00:25:56,695 --> 00:25:58,402
Get in! Watch out!

393
00:26:03,054 --> 00:26:05,125
So now what the hell do we do?

394
00:26:19,529 --> 00:26:21,323
How many cars are we
supposed to cut in?

395
00:26:23,490 --> 00:26:24,890
Twenty. Why?

396
00:26:24,977 --> 00:26:26,281
Twenty cars. Okay.

397
00:26:26,530 --> 00:26:28,362
See the switch stand
up ahead of us?

398
00:26:28,774 --> 00:26:30,645
The switch stand. Yeah?
Uh-huh.

399
00:26:31,249 --> 00:26:33,809
Take a look in the rear view
mirror. You see the one behind us?

400
00:26:34,135 --> 00:26:35,842
Way back there. You see it? Uh-huh.

401
00:26:35,929 --> 00:26:38,969
There's exactly 21 cars
between the two stands.

402
00:26:39,055 --> 00:26:40,120
Don't ask me how I know.

403
00:26:40,494 --> 00:26:42,086
So why is it that

404
00:26:42,172 --> 00:26:45,039
there's still more than four and
a half cars that are yet to clear?

405
00:26:47,533 --> 00:26:48,645
Because I...

406
00:26:49,096 --> 00:26:50,007
Excuse me?

407
00:26:50,093 --> 00:26:51,800
- Because I cut...
- Because what?

408
00:26:51,887 --> 00:26:53,201
I cut in too many cars.

409
00:26:53,287 --> 00:26:54,840
Cut in too many cars. Huh?

410
00:26:55,253 --> 00:26:57,037
Maybe if you weren't on
my ass the whole time.

411
00:26:57,133 --> 00:26:59,156
I might be able to think
straight and do my job.

412
00:26:59,252 --> 00:27:00,163
What do you mean.
"Maybe. If I..."

413
00:27:00,288 --> 00:27:02,081
You been on my ass this whole
trip! You're blaming it on me?

414
00:27:02,167 --> 00:27:03,596
I'm just saying.
Pick a goddamn job!

415
00:27:03,692 --> 00:27:05,044
I got my job!
You pick one!

416
00:27:05,131 --> 00:27:07,126
I pull the throttle. You pull
the pin! It's one or the other!

417
00:27:07,212 --> 00:27:08,516
You're five pins too many.

418
00:27:08,612 --> 00:27:10,444
Pull the pins. You're
right. Pull the pins.

419
00:27:10,530 --> 00:27:12,170
I've had my training!
All right?

420
00:27:12,247 --> 00:27:14,807
Yeah. But we're out here in the
real world. This isn't training.

421
00:27:14,894 --> 00:27:17,521
In training. They just give you
an F. Out here. You get killed.

422
00:27:17,608 --> 00:27:19,123
I screwed up. Okay?
Yes. You did.

423
00:27:19,209 --> 00:27:20,638
Stop and roll back and
I'll cut the empties.

424
00:27:20,734 --> 00:27:21,683
Roll back?

425
00:27:23,333 --> 00:27:24,637
Oh. Lord.

426
00:27:24,810 --> 00:27:26,402
We can't stop out
here on the main.

427
00:27:26,526 --> 00:27:27,716
We're more than
a mile out on the main.

428
00:27:27,811 --> 00:27:29,039
More than a mile
to the next stop.

429
00:27:29,135 --> 00:27:32,165
You don't take a consist this
size that distance in reverse.

430
00:27:34,410 --> 00:27:37,085
Fine. Then we'll make the
turn at the next siding.

431
00:27:37,171 --> 00:27:39,320
The next siding's
not for 10 miles.

432
00:27:39,406 --> 00:27:41,324
We do that. We're late.
I don't run late.

433
00:27:41,410 --> 00:27:42,811
Just green-sheet it
and we'll move on.

434
00:27:42,887 --> 00:27:45,160
Come on. We green-sheet it and
it's my ass! Cut me some slack.

435
00:27:45,246 --> 00:27:47,203
What do you mean. It's
your ass? You're a Colson.

436
00:27:47,289 --> 00:27:48,325
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

437
00:27:48,411 --> 00:27:50,166
That means you can call your
uncle and they'll take care of it.

438
00:27:50,252 --> 00:27:51,288
Is that what
this is about?

439
00:27:51,375 --> 00:27:52,410
No. It's about
the five cars too many.

440
00:27:52,487 --> 00:27:54,683
We're going to stop. Roll back
and cut those empties!

441
00:27:54,769 --> 00:27:57,320
This may be your engine.
But it's my goddamn train.

442
00:27:57,445 --> 00:27:59,162
Yes. It is.
I'm the goddamn conductor!

443
00:27:59,286 --> 00:28:00,763
- That's true.
- 1206, check in.

444
00:28:00,850 --> 00:28:02,490
I'll write you up and
green-sheet your ass.

445
00:28:02,566 --> 00:28:03,516
Will you?
How about that?

446
00:28:03,612 --> 00:28:06,719
1206, this is dispatch. What's your
location? Over.

447
00:28:06,891 --> 00:28:08,560
- Something is funny?
- No.

448
00:28:08,646 --> 00:28:10,401
What the hell are you laughing
at? What are you laughing at?

449
00:28:10,526 --> 00:28:12,799
Because it's funny.
You're a funny guy.

450
00:28:13,010 --> 00:28:16,040
Well-trained. But funny.
Yeah. This is 1206.

451
00:28:18,006 --> 00:28:19,646
We're 60 miles
from Wilkins.

452
00:28:19,809 --> 00:28:21,449
Forty minutes
out of Fuller Yard.

453
00:28:22,207 --> 00:28:23,761
Negative. 1206. Clear your
train at the next siding

454
00:28:23,847 --> 00:28:25,487
until further instructed.
Over.

455
00:28:25,573 --> 00:28:26,925
What's up?

456
00:28:27,050 --> 00:28:30,080
There's an unmanned train out of
Fuller, on the northbound track. Over.

457
00:28:31,653 --> 00:28:33,322
On our track?

458
00:28:34,012 --> 00:28:35,365
A coaster?

459
00:28:35,451 --> 00:28:36,515
1206. We don't have
all the details yet.

460
00:28:36,611 --> 00:28:38,721
Just proceed to the next
siding and hold tight. Over.

461
00:28:38,808 --> 00:28:40,476
Next siding's
not for 10 miles.

462
00:28:41,330 --> 00:28:42,720
Affirmative, 1206.

463
00:28:42,807 --> 00:28:44,120
Just get in that
siding and sit tight

464
00:28:44,207 --> 00:28:45,521
until we give you
the all-clear. Over.

465
00:28:45,607 --> 00:28:46,959
Affirmative.

466
00:28:50,086 --> 00:28:51,802
It's coming right at us.

467
00:29:00,453 --> 00:29:04,001
More word on that runaway freight
train in rural Pennsylvania.

468
00:29:04,164 --> 00:29:06,408
The train, A WVR777,

469
00:29:06,485 --> 00:29:08,489
otherwise known as 777,

470
00:29:08,566 --> 00:29:10,474
left Fuller
Yard in northern PA

471
00:29:10,609 --> 00:29:12,517
sometime before 8:00 A.M. This morning

472
00:29:12,728 --> 00:29:14,272
and no one was on-board.

473
00:29:14,406 --> 00:29:16,842
Live, local, late-breaking.

474
00:29:16,967 --> 00:29:19,681
The engineer, they say, made an
error in controlling the train.

475
00:29:19,892 --> 00:29:21,244
Before leaving
the locomotive,

476
00:29:21,330 --> 00:29:23,354
he intended to apply
the independent brakes.

477
00:29:23,450 --> 00:29:25,281
And then by the time
he realized his mistake,

478
00:29:25,406 --> 00:29:28,005
the train was going too fast
for him to climb back on.

479
00:29:28,331 --> 00:29:29,760
We're being told
now by a spokesperson

480
00:29:29,923 --> 00:29:31,352
for the Public
Utilities Commission

481
00:29:31,448 --> 00:29:33,999
that this employee
will be held accountable.

482
00:29:42,563 --> 00:29:43,963
Connie?
Yeah.

483
00:29:44,049 --> 00:29:46,715
Headquarters is
on the phone. It's Galvin.

484
00:29:53,486 --> 00:29:54,886
Mr. Galvin. How are you?

485
00:29:54,963 --> 00:29:56,315
God damn it.
How could this happen?

486
00:29:56,728 --> 00:30:00,525
It's an unfortunate combination
of human error and bad luck.

487
00:30:00,602 --> 00:30:01,676
Luck?

488
00:30:01,762 --> 00:30:04,007
I was a yardmaster
for 10 years. Ms. Hooper.

489
00:30:04,083 --> 00:30:05,877
Luck has no business
in a rail yard.

490
00:30:06,404 --> 00:30:07,881
What are we worried about
in terms of cargo?

491
00:30:08,006 --> 00:30:09,914
Well. Obviously.
The diesel fuel's a concern.

492
00:30:10,202 --> 00:30:11,679
No, I said cargo.

493
00:30:11,842 --> 00:30:13,367
Okay. Well.
Cars 7 through 10

494
00:30:13,443 --> 00:30:16,483
and 16 through 19 are carrying
a chemical called molten phenol.

495
00:30:16,570 --> 00:30:18,401
We're still trying to
connect with the shipper

496
00:30:18,488 --> 00:30:19,917
to determine
exactly what that is.

497
00:30:20,003 --> 00:30:21,643
It's used in
the manufacture of glue.

498
00:30:21,729 --> 00:30:23,360
Can you hold on
one moment?

499
00:30:24,203 --> 00:30:25,393
You know about
molten phenol?

500
00:30:25,527 --> 00:30:26,716
Yes.

501
00:30:28,922 --> 00:30:32,154
Mr. Galvin. We have
an FRA inspector here.

502
00:30:32,250 --> 00:30:33,794
May I put you on speaker?

503
00:30:36,805 --> 00:30:40,152
Region 2 Federal Safety Inspector
Scott Werner. How can I help?

504
00:30:40,248 --> 00:30:42,482
