10 cars into the siding.

750
00:48:04,138 --> 00:48:05,298
Yes!

751
00:48:40,417 --> 00:48:43,170
Frank, go to 6. Frank, go to 6.

752
00:48:44,378 --> 00:48:45,615
Yeah. I'm at 6. Go.

753
00:48:46,382 --> 00:48:47,811
They're evacuating Arklow.

754
00:48:48,454 --> 00:48:49,739
They're going to
derail the train.

755
00:48:50,660 --> 00:48:51,571
What are they using?

756
00:48:51,657 --> 00:48:53,565
Standard DRE.

757
00:48:53,939 --> 00:48:55,330
Yeah.
A portable derailer.

758
00:49:00,221 --> 00:49:01,612
What are you doing?

759
00:49:01,698 --> 00:49:04,210
I got a look at that train's
last coupler knuckle. It was open.

760
00:49:05,102 --> 00:49:06,771
We take off right now.
We get back on the main.

761
00:49:06,857 --> 00:49:08,373
We can chase it
down in reverse.

762
00:49:08,459 --> 00:49:09,648
Chase?
Whoa. Wait a minute.

763
00:49:09,734 --> 00:49:12,333
The only way to stop that kind
of power. Grab it by the tail.

764
00:49:12,420 --> 00:49:13,647
Boom. Gun it in
the opposite direction.

765
00:49:13,733 --> 00:49:14,923
We can't just chase it down.
If it goes down.

766
00:49:15,019 --> 00:49:16,371
We're going to be
a wreck on a wreck.

767
00:49:17,416 --> 00:49:20,763
Doesn't matter. There's a good
chance the derailer won't work.

768
00:49:21,022 --> 00:49:23,017
It's called a derailer.
For Christ's sake!

769
00:49:23,093 --> 00:49:24,522
That's what they do!
A train that size

770
00:49:24,618 --> 00:49:27,572
going that fast. It will vaporize
anything that gets in its way.

771
00:49:27,658 --> 00:49:29,087
Bullshit!
They wouldn't use it if...

772
00:49:29,174 --> 00:49:31,494
They're wrong. All right?
They're wrong.

773
00:49:32,137 --> 00:49:33,374
Are you in or are you out?

774
00:49:33,460 --> 00:49:35,407
You want to get yourself
killed. You do it alone.

775
00:49:35,494 --> 00:49:37,565
You know what? Ask your
wife what she thinks.

776
00:49:38,179 --> 00:49:39,483
Wait!

777
00:49:43,175 --> 00:49:45,007
If you're right and
that derailer fails.

778
00:49:45,093 --> 00:49:46,887
What are the odds it
makes it to Stanton?

779
00:49:47,059 --> 00:49:49,371
You saw the train.
What do you think?

780
00:50:14,372 --> 00:50:16,770
1206. This is Connie Hooper.
Are you there?

781
00:50:18,131 --> 00:50:19,417
1206. Over.

782
00:50:19,493 --> 00:50:21,287
Just wanted to see
how you boys are doing.

783
00:50:24,375 --> 00:50:27,089
We're doing about 60
mile an hour. Connie.

784
00:50:27,376 --> 00:50:29,927
Sorry? Frank.
I don't understand.

785
00:50:30,052 --> 00:50:31,960
We're going
after your train.

786
00:50:32,056 --> 00:50:33,936
1206, I'm not hearing you.

787
00:50:34,013 --> 00:50:35,442
The rear knuckle
was left open.

788
00:50:35,538 --> 00:50:37,926
So if we can catch up. We can
tie it on to our locomotive.

789
00:50:38,012 --> 00:50:39,489
Try and slow down 777.

790
00:50:39,575 --> 00:50:40,688
Frank. You can't.

791
00:50:40,774 --> 00:50:41,848
We already are.

792
00:50:41,934 --> 00:50:43,574
Portable derailer's
not going to cut it. Connie.

793
00:50:44,178 --> 00:50:45,722
Who said anything
about a derailer?

794
00:50:46,173 --> 00:50:48,849
Dispatch. They said that
they're evacuating Arklow.

795
00:50:48,935 --> 00:50:49,971
Two plus two is four.

796
00:50:51,496 --> 00:50:52,973
It's Ned. He said he's still
following... No. No. No.

797
00:50:53,059 --> 00:50:55,293
Tell him I'll call him back.
Get me Galvin. Now.

798
00:50:55,380 --> 00:50:59,005
Frank. That train is carrying
30.000 gallons of toxic chemicals.

799
00:50:59,139 --> 00:51:02,687
They had a window before. But that
train is going into populated areas.

800
00:51:02,774 --> 00:51:04,126
There's no way
they'd derail it now.

801
00:51:06,418 --> 00:51:07,646
Are you sure about that?

802
00:51:09,372 --> 00:51:10,925
Look. Let me
make some calls.

803
00:51:11,213 --> 00:51:13,121
Make some calls. Please.

804
00:51:22,290 --> 00:51:23,815
What do you think? Do you
think they can catch up?

805
00:51:24,774 --> 00:51:26,970
Possibly.
But even if they do.

806
00:51:27,056 --> 00:51:30,403
We're talking about coupling at 10
times the normal speed. In reverse.

807
00:51:31,372 --> 00:51:33,127
I thought you were
in favor of derailment.

808
00:51:33,213 --> 00:51:35,409
Yeah. When they were in the
middle of nowhere. Not now.

809
00:51:35,495 --> 00:51:36,924
It's just town
after town out there!

810
00:51:37,011 --> 00:51:38,679
Mr. Galvin says he'd
have to call you back.

811
00:51:38,775 --> 00:51:40,770
This is Connie Hooper
for Mr. Galvin.

812
00:51:40,856 --> 00:51:42,045
Mr. Galvin is in a meeting.

813
00:51:42,170 --> 00:51:45,249
Then maybe you can tell me. Is the
company planning on derailing 777?

814
00:51:45,335 --> 00:51:47,723
Last I heard. Galvin
was dead set against it.

815
00:51:47,809 --> 00:51:49,478
I'm sorry, I'd really like
to help you, Ms. Hooper.

816
00:51:49,574 --> 00:51:51,089
But I'm not at liberty
to give you that information.

817
00:51:51,175 --> 00:51:53,410
No. Of course
you're not at liberty to.

818
00:51:53,851 --> 00:51:55,328
Frank's right.

819
00:52:02,214 --> 00:52:04,649
What's the fastest you've
taken a single engine like this?

820
00:52:05,417 --> 00:52:06,481
Unattached?
Yeah.

821
00:52:06,577 --> 00:52:08,447
Fifty. 55.

822
00:52:09,454 --> 00:52:10,682
Of course.
I was going forward.

823
00:52:11,411 --> 00:52:12,571
1206, you there?

824
00:52:13,252 --> 00:52:14,527
This is 1206. Over.

825
00:52:14,652 --> 00:52:15,889
Frank, you're right.

826
00:52:15,975 --> 00:52:18,402
About the derailment.

827
00:52:18,498 --> 00:52:20,368
They're planning an attempt
outside of Arklow.

828
00:52:23,417 --> 00:52:25,009
Tell them idiots
it isn't going to work.

829
00:52:25,134 --> 00:52:26,764
That portable derailer.
It's worthless.

830
00:52:26,851 --> 00:52:28,165
She already told us.

831
00:52:29,296 --> 00:52:32,758
Frank. This is Oscar Galvin.
VP of Operations.

832
00:52:32,854 --> 00:52:35,482
Patched in at his request.
Open mike.

833
00:52:36,096 --> 00:52:40,133
Yeah. We're derailing 777.
Frank. It's a done decision.

834
00:52:40,210 --> 00:52:42,598
Like it or not, it's our
best option at this stage.

835
00:52:42,694 --> 00:52:44,928
There will be less collateral
damage in Arklow.

836
00:52:45,293 --> 00:52:46,645
It's already being evacuated.

837
00:52:46,731 --> 00:52:49,484
And we can't let 777
make it to Stanton.

838
00:52:49,570 --> 00:52:51,603
Look. Mr. Galvin.
With all due respect.

839
00:52:51,689 --> 00:52:53,243
I've been railroading
28 years.

840
00:52:54,048 --> 00:52:56,436
I'm telling you. We got a
real chance to stop this thing.

841
00:52:56,532 --> 00:52:57,884
No. We already tried.

842
00:52:57,971 --> 00:53:01,241
That was from the front.
We're long hood lead back.

843
00:53:01,327 --> 00:53:04,243
It's a different situation.
We got more control now.

844
00:53:07,014 --> 00:53:09,402
What if I cancel the derailer
and you fail. Frank?

845
00:53:10,371 --> 00:53:12,203
That train will be doing
70 miles an hour

846
00:53:12,289 --> 00:53:14,284
into that elevated
S- curve in Stanton.

847
00:53:14,370 --> 00:53:16,087
The damage will
be 100 times worse.

848
00:53:16,173 --> 00:53:20,162
Right. I'm just telling you. The
portable derailer is worthless.

849
00:53:20,613 --> 00:53:23,212
You got too much train
traveling entirely too fast.

850
00:53:23,970 --> 00:53:26,837
Maybe 1206 should just
stay on it as a backup.

851
00:53:26,971 --> 00:53:30,923
Look. I am not jeopardizing
more personnel and more property

852
00:53:31,009 --> 00:53:33,685
just because some engineer
wants to play hero.

853
00:53:33,771 --> 00:53:35,488
End of discussion!

854
00:53:35,967 --> 00:53:38,691
That train is our property.
It's our decision!

855
00:53:39,813 --> 00:53:42,891
Now you stop your pursuit
or I will fire you!

856
00:53:43,495 --> 00:53:45,490
Fire.
You already did.

857
00:53:49,815 --> 00:53:51,484
Already did what?

858
00:53:52,529 --> 00:53:53,929
You've already fired me.

859
00:53:55,406 --> 00:53:59,760
I received my 90-day notice
in the mail 72 days ago.

860
00:54:00,614 --> 00:54:02,685
Forced early retirement.
Half benefits.

861
00:54:10,166 --> 00:54:13,848
So you're going to risk your
life for us with three weeks left.

862
00:54:15,526 --> 00:54:16,879
Not for you.

863
00:54:18,528 --> 00:54:19,880
I'm not doing it for you.

864
00:54:21,530 --> 00:54:23,803
Frank.
Let me see that thing.

865
00:54:28,128 --> 00:54:30,641
Mr. Galvin. This is Will
Colson. Your conductor.

866
00:54:33,892 --> 00:54:36,318
I'm letting you know. We're
going to run this bitch down.

867
00:54:36,932 --> 00:54:40,566
Maybe you didn't hear what I just
said. Colson. I will fire you!

868
00:54:42,053 --> 00:54:46,119
Well. That's too bad. I was
just starting to like this job.

869
00:54:48,287 --> 00:54:52,525
God damn it, you listen to me! You
son of a bitch! You will be fired!

870
00:54:52,612 --> 00:54:55,930
You're breaking up. Sorry.
You're...

871
00:55:00,293 --> 00:55:03,247
- This garbage is...
- Sir. I think they're gone.

872
00:55:06,613 --> 00:55:08,522
This is your
headache now. Hooper.

873
00:55:08,608 --> 00:55:12,761
Now you get them off the main or
consider yourself shit-canned. Too!

874
00:55:14,324 --> 00:55:15,724
I like them.

875
00:55:16,405 --> 00:55:18,285
Bring up Beech Siding
to Arklow.

876
00:55:18,812 --> 00:55:21,603
Take a look behind me, you can
see emergency evacuation measures

877
00:55:21,689 --> 00:55:24,125
are currently in effect right
here in the tiny town of Arklow.

878
00:55:29,889 --> 00:55:31,433
The lash-up was a no-go.

879
00:55:36,046 --> 00:55:38,673
1206 to Fuller Yard.
Connie. Are you there? Over.

880
00:55:38,769 --> 00:55:41,320
Frank. I'm real sorry
about Galvin.

881
00:55:41,406 --> 00:55:43,161
That's okay.
Listen. Listen. Is he off?

882
00:55:43,248 --> 00:55:44,245
Yeah. He's gone.

883
00:55:44,331 --> 00:55:45,847
Okay. Listen up.

884
00:55:45,923 --> 00:55:47,352
I'm going to need you
to do us a favor.

885
00:55:47,448 --> 00:55:51,323
I need you to keep us posted on
the speed and location of 777.

886
00:55:51,409 --> 00:55:52,953
Location and speed.
Over.

887
00:55:55,331 --> 00:55:56,722
Connie?

888
00:55:58,726 --> 00:56:00,683
Frank. 777's
9 miles out of Arklow.

889
00:56:00,769 --> 00:56:01,958
You got some
catching up to do.

890
00:56:02,044 --> 00:56:03,320
9 miles out of Arklow.

891
00:56:18,367 --> 00:56:20,199
What did you say
your wife's first name was?

892
00:56:20,285 --> 00:56:21,282
Darcy.

893
00:56:21,369 --> 00:56:23,315
So. What was the long story
you didn't want to make long?

894
00:56:26,288 --> 00:56:27,880
I come home from
work two weeks ago

895
00:56:27,967 --> 00:56:29,846
and she's
texting on the phone.

896
00:56:29,923 --> 00:56:32,484
I ask her who with.
She says. "Nobody."

897
00:56:33,126 --> 00:56:34,766
I say. "Let me see
the phone." She says no.

898
00:56:34,843 --> 00:56:37,202
This goes on
five or six times.

899
00:56:37,327 --> 00:56:39,686
Wait. You're losing me.
She's texting...

900
00:56:39,926 --> 00:56:41,479
There's this guy
we both went to school with.

901
00:56:41,566 --> 00:56:43,637
He's a cop.
He's a PA state trooper.

902
00:56:43,723 --> 00:56:46,284
He's always had a thing
for Darcy. Going way back.

903
00:56:46,370 --> 00:56:47,838
1206, where are you?

904
00:56:47,924 --> 00:56:51,559
1206 here. Connie. We're
just passing milepost 5-7.

905
00:56:51,645 --> 00:56:53,237
You're about a mile
and a half behind.

906
00:56:55,529 --> 00:56:57,437
How far out of Arklow
is 777?

907
00:56:57,524 --> 00:57:00,036
Seven and a half miles. It picked
up speed. You better step on it.

908
00:57:00,123 --> 00:57:02,367
I'm stepping on it. In it.
Around it and through it. Connie.

909
00:57:02,443 --> 00:57:03,959
Thank you. Over.

910
00:57:04,927 --> 00:57:08,437
She's texting on the phone. I keep on
asking for it. She keeps on saying no.

911
00:57:09,521 --> 00:57:11,640
She starts to walk
away and I grab for it.

912
00:57:12,686 --> 00:57:14,354
You hit her?
No. No. No.

913
00:57:16,445 --> 00:57:19,236
I mean. I scared her.
But I didn't hit her.

914
00:57:21,048 --> 00:57:22,803
Anyway. I drive
to this guy's house

915
00:57:22,890 --> 00:57:24,357
and tell him we need to talk.
Let's take a ride.

916
00:57:24,443 --> 00:57:26,198
He jumps in my truck
and starts in with.

917
00:57:26,285 --> 00:57:28,672
"You got it all wrong.
We're just friends."

918
00:57:28,768 --> 00:57:30,792
Then he stops once he sees

919
00:57:31,607 --> 00:57:33,870
the gun I got sitting on the dash. Oh!

920
00:57:35,683 --> 00:57:38,838
I look him in the eye and say. "She's
my wife. You find a new friend."

921
00:57:38,924 --> 00:57:40,238
You pulled a gun on a cop?

922
00:57:40,325 --> 00:57:41,638
Frank?

923
00:57:41,725 --> 00:57:44,755
Frank. 777 just
passed milepost 61.

924
00:57:46,002 --> 00:57:47,162
Thank you. Connie.

925
00:57:47,249 --> 00:57:49,080
- You want to hear the kicker?
- Yes. I do.

926
00:57:50,327 --> 00:57:53,233
It wasn't even him that was texting
her. It was my sister-in-law.

927
00:57:54,767 --> 00:57:57,318
Anyway. By the time I got home.
His buddy's waiting for me.

928
00:57:57,405 --> 00:58:00,397
Just waiting to serve me
with this restraining order.

929
00:58:02,487 --> 00:58:03,878
Darcy wouldn't
even look at me.

930
00:58:07,206 --> 00:58:09,709
So I'm living
with my brother.

931
00:58:09,805 --> 00:58:12,758
There was a hearing today. The
judge ordered a 30-day extension.

932
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:18,676
It's like one day
everything is going okay.

933
00:58:19,366 --> 00:58:20,996
And the next. It's all
falling apart faster

934
00:58:21,083 --> 00:58:22,272
than you can put
it back together.

935
00:58:22,368 --> 00:58:24,554
Yeah.
Never too late. Though.

936
00:58:34,039 --> 00:58:36,839
The plan to
derail this 39-car runaway train

937
00:58:36,926 --> 00:58:38,556
is just minutes away now.

938
00:58:38,642 --> 00:58:40,599
There's a tremendous
amount of activity going on.

939
00:58:40,685 --> 00:58:43,677
Will this train be
able to be stopped?

940
00:58:45,960 --> 00:58:48,875
1206. Connie. We're just
passing milepost 6-2.

941
00:58:48,961 --> 00:58:50,314
Milepost 6-2, over.

942
00:58:50,400 --> 00:58:51,954
Still a mile gap.
Maybe more.

943
00:58:52,040 --> 00:58:53,709
We're not
gaining on her. Frank.

944
00:58:54,121 --> 00:58:55,790
Hold on.

945
00:59:00,920 --> 00:59:02,714
It's just like
the shooting range!

946
00:59:02,800 --> 00:59:06,147
All right. Here we go! Come on!
Let's go! This is it! It's game time!

947
00:59:10,923 --> 00:59:13,637
Remember. We're aiming
for the red circular button!

948
00:59:18,518 --> 00:59:19,554
Now!

949
00:59:21,884 --> 00:59:25,356
Hold your fire! You're shooting
the fuel cap. God damn it!

950
00:59:25,442 --> 00:59:26,747
Hold your fire!

951
00:59:26,843 --> 00:59:29,317
We were aiming to disable
it by firing shotgun rounds

952
00:59:29,403 --> 00:59:33,556
at a fuel stop safety switch,
and so some shots were fired.

953
00:59:33,642 --> 00:59:36,433
That safety
switch is a mighty small target.

954
00:59:36,519 --> 00:59:38,840
And it's right
next to a fuel tank.

955
00:59:43,481 --> 00:59:45,313
We're not going to
catch it before Arklow.

956
00:59:45,400 --> 00:59:48,267
Frank. You're closing the
gap. You should cut your speed.

957
00:59:48,401 --> 00:59:50,597
Allow yourself some stopping
distance. Just in case.

958
00:59:50,684 --> 00:59:53,273
No can do. Connie. If we slow
down now. We'll never catch it.

959
00:59:53,359 --> 00:59:54,760
Not before Stanton. Over.

960
00:59:54,846 --> 00:59:56,121
It's your call.

961
00:59:56,917 --> 01:00:00,120
However, we have now also learned
that two railroad employees

962
01:00:00,197 --> 01:00:04,436
are now in pursuit of train
777 in a single locomotive.

963
01:00:04,522 --> 01:00:05,827
It is unclear
what their plan is...

964
01:00:05,922 --> 01:00:08,521
Connie Hooper for you.

965
01:00:08,598 --> 01:00:11,801
Did I or did I not tell you
to get 1206 off the main?

966
01:00:11,878 --> 01:00:13,230
I asked them nicely.

967
01:00:19,320 --> 01:00:21,554
You're 100% sure that
derailer won't work?

968
01:00:21,641 --> 01:00:23,914
Yes. 100%? No.

969
01:00:24,000 --> 01:00:25,074
Which one is it?

970
01:00:27,836 --> 01:00:29,792
50-50.
Pretty funny.

971
01:00:29,879 --> 01:00:31,912
And if it does?

972
01:00:31,998 --> 01:00:35,633
If it does. Then
we're a wreck on a wreck.

973
01:00:37,081 --> 01:00:38,913
I'm here with FRA
official Gene Devereaux.

974
01:00:38,999 --> 01:00:41,032
This train is getting close.
How is this going to work?

975
01:00:41,118 --> 01:00:43,554
Basically,
it works like a ramp.

976
01:00:44,724 --> 01:00:45,875
The train comes along,

977
01:00:45,961 --> 01:00:49,673
this piece here will lift the
flange and pull it outside the rail.

978
01:00:49,759 --> 01:00:53,634
That will cause the train to
flip over on its right-hand side.

979
01:00:53,720 --> 01:00:55,235
Son of a bitch won't
even know what hit it.

980
01:01:03,281 --> 01:01:05,113
Train is about four minutes out!

981
01:01:05,199 --> 01:01:06,513
Guys. Come on. Get it started!

982
01:01:07,041 --> 01:01:08,191
Guys. Come on!

983
01:01:30,517 --> 01:01:32,109
It has not succeeded! What?

984
01:01:32,196 --> 01:01:33,433
What in the hell was that?

985
01:01:33,519 --> 01:01:37,470
That was 10 million pounds
of train. Mr. Galvin!

986
01:01:37,557 --> 01:01:39,753
And this is the sound
